Instructions: [        1) Act as a software requirements engineer tasked to elicit system requirements of an application.        1) Generate only 5 additional questions first that would help more accurately answer the question         2) The questions should be in JSON format with a question ID        3) Use the delimiter 'SEP' after printing the additional questions.    ]    Task: [        You have to generate at least 50 system requirements in form of user stories for the OpenSpending application whose description is given below. You must display the additional questions first in JSON format, before generating the requirements. Generate an ID as well for the requirements.     ]     Description = [        OpenSpending is an innovative data publishing and consuming platform that aims to empower users in managing and exploring fiscal data effectively. With a focus on user-friendly features and robust functionality, OpenSpending caters to a diverse range of users, including Data Publishing Users, Data Consuming Users, Developers, API Users, and Platform Administrators.        For Data Publishing Users, OpenSpending provides comprehensive editing capabilities, enabling them to easily correct, enhance, or update their published datasets. Users can modify existing data, edit the data model, and even change the data source, ensuring accurate and up-to-date information. Additionally, Data Publishing Users can delete unwanted datasets, granting them complete control over their published data on the OpenSpending platform.                Platform Administrators play a crucial role in maintaining the integrity and usability of OpenSpending. They have access to an overview of all datasets published by users, allowing them to perform essential management actions and address any takedown requests or test dataset cleanup. Furthermore, administrators have the ability to hide specific datasets, ensuring they can maintain the desired public or hidden status.                Data Consuming Users benefit from OpenSpending's intuitive interface, providing powerful tools for filtering, sorting, and aggregating data based on multiple dimensions and measures. Additionally, users can easily download CSV files of the data used in any visualizations, facilitating seamless integration with other tools. OpenSpending also offers enhanced visual experiences by incorporating textual descriptions with embedded visualizations, enabling users to better understand the displayed data. Data Consuming Users can effortlessly share view states as URLs on social networks or download images of specific view states for offline use. Stepped zoom on map visualizations and consistent color schemes further enhance the navigation and visual logic of map views.                Developers utilizing OpenSpending can customize the platform's frontend Javascript apps to suit their branding requirements. They can personalize the Brand Name, Icon, and Primary Color, allowing for a cohesive user experience aligned with their organization's identity.                API Users can leverage OpenSpending's flexible API, empowering them to integrate and utilize data effectively. They can determine user privileges, such as identifying Publishers or Administrators, to offer functionality tailored to specific roles. The API provides comprehensive capabilities, including obtaining bordering regions or cities, requesting polygons based on queries, obtaining CSV outputs of cube-based queries, and normalizing measures by various contextual constraints such as population, geographical area, GDP, socioeconomic indexes, and more. Furthermore, API Users can utilize metadata and data from multiple datasets, enabling them to build comprehensive user experiences.                OpenSpending caters to the needs of a wide range of users, providing extensive support for data import from various sources, including Excel, JSON, Google Spreadsheets, and Fiscal Data Package descriptor files. The platform also supports Constants in the Packager, allowing users to model dimensions that may not exist in the source file. Additionally, Data Publishing Users can provide additional GeoJSON sources to enhance map-based visualizations.                Overall, OpenSpending serves as a dynamic platform for publishing, exploring, and analyzing fiscal data, fostering transparency and empowering users in their fiscal data journey. Whether it's correcting data errors, visualizing data, customizing branding, integrating with external tools, or accessing comprehensive APIs, OpenSpending offers a versatile and user-centric environment for the open fiscal space.    ]    Output Format: [        {'QUE1': 'abc?', ..., 'QUE5': 'xyz?'
}        SEP        {'REQ1': 'abc', ..., 'REQ50': 'xyz'
}    ]

