Instructions: [        1) Act as a software requirements engineer tasked to elicit system requirements of an application.        1) Generate only 5 additional questions first that would help more accurately answer the question         2) The questions should be in JSON format with a question ID        3) Use the delimiter 'SEP' after printing the additional questions.    ]    Task: [        You have to generate at least 50 system requirements in form of user stories for the Data package toolbox application whose description is given below. You must display the additional questions first in JSON format, before generating the requirements. Generate an ID as well for the requirements.     ]     Description = [        The Data Package Toolbox is a versatile application designed to meet the needs of developers, researchers, publishers, and data analysts. The objective of this tool is to streamline the process of accessing, analyzing, and visualizing data in various programming languages and software platforms. By supporting seamless integration with popular tools such as Node, Julia, R, Excel, SPSS, STATA, Python, Clojure, C++, and more, the Data Package Toolbox enables users to effortlessly import Data Packages and start utilizing the data for analysis and visualization purposes.        The motivation behind the Data Package Toolbox is to empower users to work with data in a standardized and efficient manner. Developers benefit from quick and easy integration of Data Packages into their workflows, enabling them to focus on building applications and performing data analysis. Researchers can rapidly import Data Packages into their preferred analysis environments, allowing them to leverage the wide array of available tools and expedite their research process. Publishers can enhance the usability of their data by adding type information and visualizations, increasing its value to others and enabling seamless integration with visualization programs. Furthermore, the Data Package Toolbox supports saving new visualizations, facilitating collaboration and sharing among researchers.        This comprehensive tool provides validation and profiling capabilities, allowing researchers and publisher to ensure that their data adheres to Data Package standards and identify any potential issues. By offering integrations with various platforms such as Elasticsearch, SPSS, EPrints, Mongo, DSpace, Feather, HDF5, and more, the Data Package Toolbox enables smooth data integration within pipelines and data management systems.        In addition to facilitating data analysis and integration, the Data Package Toolbox caters to the needs of publishers, repository managers, and civic tech activists. It offers features like metadata enhancement, data validation, and data quality assessment, ensuring that published data is reliable, transparent, and conforms to transparency commitments. The tool also facilitates data preview and embedding, allowing publishers to present interactive previews of their data and track user engagement. Furthermore, the Data Package Toolbox supports the generation of reproducible steps and methodology documentation, promoting transparency and enabling data reusability.        Overall, the Data Package Toolbox is a comprehensive application that aims to simplify data access, analysis, and publication. With its wide range of integrations, validation capabilities, and collaboration features, it caters to the needs of developers, researchers, publishers, and data managers, empowering them to work efficiently, enhance data quality, and foster data transparency.    ]    Output Format: [        {'QUE1': 'abc?', ..., 'QUE5': 'xyz?'
}        SEP        {'REQ1': 'abc', ..., 'REQ50': 'xyz'
}    ]

