r research to aid stakeholders in evaluating the CMS's suitability for their specific needs and making informed decisions.        5. Supporting designers in implementing new social media wireframes and determining the design direction for the beta social page in the absence of established brand guidelines.        6. Collaborating with engineers to prioritize features and elements of the future social element page, considering feasibility and technical constraints.        7. Enabling user researchers to test the effectiveness of the research plan, refining the OLPA task script, and conducting in-person interviews with internal users.        8. Enhancing the content editing experience by implementing user-friendly search functionalities to easily locate and edit content.        9. Providing a distraction-free user experience during prototype testing to ensure research participants can focus on the workflow without being overwhelmed by the prototype's appearance.        10. Supporting the overall project management and planning processes by providing updated roadmaps, facilitating communication with stakeholders, and ensuring easy access to relevant reports and documentation.                The NSF Web Redesign Application caters to a diverse range of users, including team members, developers, stakeholders, NSF employees, content editors, researchers, CMS administrators, NSF administrators, visual designers, web recruiter managers, workshop attendees, authors, and potential research participants. By addressing their specific needs and objectives, the application empowers them to contribute effectively to the web redesign project, collaborate seamlessly, and make informed decisions.                Overall, the NSF Web Redesign Application serves as a comprehensive platform that fosters collaboration, supports decision-making, and streamlines the development and deployment of a user-centric CMS for the NSF website.    ]    Output Format: [        {'QUE1': 'abc?', ..., 'QUE5': 'xyz?'
