ances as part of pipeline creation. Hydrator users can also specify explicit versions of dataset types and ensure compatibility with existing dataset instances. The system ensures that all dataset instances created by apps and hydrator pipelines are accessible as sources and sinks for other components.                With the Dataset Management Application, users can easily explore and administer datasets, perform custom administrative operations, update dataset properties, configure schema and time-to-live settings, and trigger migration processes when required. Users have the ability to specify schemas in JSON or SQL format and access detailed information about dataset properties and configuration. The application also guarantees atomicity for dataset reconfiguration and safeguards against data loss during updates.                Overall, the Dataset Management Application is a powerful and user-friendly tool that streamlines the management and utilization of datasets, ensuring seamless integration with various components, maintaining data integrity, and facilitating collaboration between developers, data scientists, and users.    ]    Output Format: [        {'QUE1': 'abc?', ..., 'QUE5': 'xyz?'
}        SEP        {'REQ1': 'abc', ..., 'REQ50': 'xyz'
}    ]

Instructions: [        1) Act as a software requirements engineer tasked to elicit system requirements of an application.        1) Generate only 5 additional questions first that would help more accurately answer the question         2) The questions should be in JSON format with a question ID        3) Use the delimiter 'SEP' after printing the additional questions.    ]    Task: [        You have to generate at least 50 system requirements in form of user stories for the NeuroHub application whose description is given below. You must display the additional questions first in JSON format, before generating the requirements. Generate an ID as well for the requirements.     ]     Description = [        NeuroHub is an advanced research management and collaboration platform designed to meet the diverse needs of neuroscientists, researchers, lab administrators, system administrators, and other stakeholders. It provides a comprehensive suite of features and tools that streamline the research workflow, enhance collaboration, and ensure data integrity and accessibility.        The primary objective of NeuroHub is to facilitate efficient installation, testing, and management of the Neurohub node on Ubuntu operating systems. System administrators can run scripts to install the Neurohub node on a fresh Ubuntu OS and test its functionality to ensure a successful installation. Release engineers can execute acceptance tests against Neurohub installations, generating detailed reports for further analysis. Investigators can view these acceptance test results, gaining insights into the level of feature completeness of the Neurohub node.                NeuroHub also caters to the needs of researchers by enabling them to digitally record subject responses on paper-based forms during MRI sessions. Users can navigate seamlessly between log books and log book pages without relying on browser back buttons, enhancing usability. Lab administrators have the flexibility to theme the Web interface graphics and colors according to their preferences.                Additionally, NeuroHub supports various file management functionalities crucial to researchers. Researchers can upload files, attach them to log book pages, and even attach entire directories containing multiple files. They can also receive alerts for any unattached files in their workspace, ensuring efficient organization. The application enables researchers to download files directly from the search results page, access files through network drives, and assign tags and metadata to files for easy categorization and retrieval. NeuroHub ensures data security by making uploaded data files non-modifiable and allowing users to revert to previous file versions if needed.                For system administrators, NeuroHub provides features such as managing backups, migrating data between different versions, and integrating with external services like Mendeley and Wormbase. The application also supports collaboration features, including shared calendars, feedback forms, shared inventory management, and collaborative spreadsheet editing. Researchers can track the evolution of experimental protocols, manage references and papers, and even share papers and notes with other researchers.                With its extensive support for metadata, NeuroHub enables researchers to attach standard metadata to various data types, such as images, behavioural observations, drug responses, and more. This facilitates easy search and understanding of data within the research community. Researchers can also establish links between different objects, allowing for association-based searching. The application incorporates revision control to track changes to files over time and ensure data provenance.                NeuroHub is designed to be scalable, user-friendly, and adaptable to individual research needs. It caters to a broad user base, including researchers, system administrators, lab administrators, investigators, MRI operators, release engineers, and supervisors. By providing a centralized platform for research management, collaboration, and data integrity, NeuroHub empowers researchers and enhances the efficiency and productivity of neuroscience research endeavors.    ]    Output Format: [        {'QUE1': 'abc?', ..., 'QUE5': 'xyz?'
}        SEP        {'REQ1': 'abc', ..., 'REQ50': 'xyz'
}    ]

