Instructions: [        1) Act as a software requirements engineer tasked to elicit system requirements of an application.        1) Generate only 5 additional questions first that would help more accurately answer the question         2) The questions should be in JSON format with a question ID        3) Use the delimiter 'SEP' after printing the additional questions.    ]    Task: [        You have to generate at least 50 system requirements in form of user stories for the Data Archive application whose description is given below. You must display the additional questions first in JSON format, before generating the requirements. Generate an ID as well for the requirements.     ]     Description = [        The University of Bath Data Archive is a comprehensive web-based application designed to streamline the process of depositing, managing, and accessing research datasets. With a user-friendly interface and seamless integration with existing University systems, the archive aims to provide a unified platform for depositors to easily deposit and maintain datasets without the need for additional software installations or extensive training. Depositors have the flexibility to deposit and manage datasets through various channels, including a simple web interface, Pure, Virtual Research Environments, and other familiar workflow tools. The primary objectives of the archive are to ensure data integrity, facilitate data discovery, promote data reuse, and comply with funder requirements and archival standards.        The motivation behind the University of Bath Data Archive is to address the needs and challenges faced by depositors, data reusers, external collaborators, research facility managers, administrators, research information managers, university IT services, developers, academic publishers, and funding bodies. For depositors, the archive offers a user-friendly interface, support for large file uploads, options for embargoes and licensing, integration with publication systems, automatic metadata population, and the ability to link datasets with project data management plans. Data reusers benefit from easy web-based search capabilities, multilingual access, preliminary file examination, example citations, DOI assignment, and persistent URLs. External collaborators can gain privileged access to data and collaborate effectively, while research facility managers can deposit facility data on behalf of researchers. Administrators have control over metadata quality, disposal policies, and system-wide querying capabilities. Research information managers can integrate the archive with CRIS, track citation counts, and link datasets with project metadata. University IT services can ensure consistent storage, integration with existing systems, and future-proofing. Developers have access to an API for seamless interaction, and academic publishers can establish persistent links between articles and datasets. Funding bodies can monitor archival plans and harvest metadata for analysis.                Overall, the University of Bath Data Archive aims to provide a comprehensive and user-friendly solution for managing research datasets, promoting data reuse and discoverability, ensuring data integrity, and complying with funder requirements and archival standards. It offers a range of features and functionalities that cater to the needs of various stakeholders involved in the research data lifecycle, fostering a collaborative and efficient research environment.    ]    Output Format: [        {'QUE1': 'abc?', ..., 'QUE5': 'xyz?'
}        SEP        {'REQ1': 'abc', ..., 'REQ50': 'xyz'
}    ]

