Instructions: [        1) Act as a software requirements engineer tasked to elicit system requirements of an application.        1) Generate only 5 additional questions first that would help more accurately answer the question         2) The questions should be in JSON format with a question ID        3) Use the delimiter 'SEP' after printing the additional questions.    ]    Task: [        You have to generate at least 50 system requirements in form of user stories for the Archivault application whose description is given below. You must display the additional questions first in JSON format, before generating the requirements. Generate an ID as well for the requirements.     ]     Description = [        Our application, called ArchiVault, is a comprehensive digital asset management system specifically designed for archivists, researchers, and donor representatives. ArchiVault aims to streamline the management and accessibility of archival materials while ensuring compliance with licensing, rights, and access restrictions. It offers a user-friendly interface and a range of features to address the diverse needs of these stakeholders.        The objectives of ArchiVault are to provide archivists with a centralized platform to efficiently manage and organize digital files, apply licenses or rights statements, mark files and groups as restricted, restrict file visibility, set automatic restriction removal dates, and add detailed restrictions and metadata. The application also supports automatic generation of technical metadata, creation of access copies and derivatives, as well as automatic assignment of unique identifiers and embedding of metadata in file headers.                For archivists, ArchiVault simplifies the process of uploading single files or batches of files, performing batch metadata editing, and managing loan documentation and inventories. It also includes features such as redaction of sensitive information, online licensing forms for transparency and efficiency, and integration with the RAC website to showcase archival collections online.                Researchers benefit from ArchiVault's robust search capabilities, allowing them to search files and collections by keyword, tags, structured data, and even by uploading images for visual search. They can access and download files, generate structured citation data, share links on social media, request analog versions, and receive notifications about digitized materials relevant to their research.                Donor representatives can use ArchiVault to access descriptive information and view images scanned from their collections. They can browse and select images for use in exhibits, reports, and other institutional needs, facilitating collaboration between archives and donors.                ArchiVault also offers administrative functionalities, including user group and role management, assignment of permissions and rights, integration with Active Directory for user authentication, and the ability for researchers to reset their own passwords.                The motivation behind ArchiVault is to enhance accessibility, collaboration, and efficiency within the archival community. By providing a comprehensive solution for managing, organizing, and accessing digital archival materials, ArchiVault empowers archivists to fulfill the mission of making archival content widely available while ensuring compliance with licensing and access restrictions. Researchers benefit from easy access to a wealth of digitized materials, and donor representatives can actively engage with their collections.                Overall, ArchiVault serves as a reliable and intuitive platform that supports archivists, researchers, and donor representatives in their respective roles, ultimately fostering the preservation and dissemination of valuable archival content.    ]    Output Format: [        {'QUE1': 'abc?', ..., 'QUE5': 'xyz?'
}        SEP        {'REQ1': 'abc', ..., 'REQ50': 'xyz'
}    ]

